Types of ML¶

Measure¶

Dissimilarity¶

It is a function $d_{i,j} = d(x_i,x_j)$ that associates each pair $ij$ with a numerical value to determine how 'distant' objects are from each other.

  • 1) Non negative $d_{i,j} ≥ 0$
  • 2) Null $d_{ii} = 0$
  • 3) Symmetry $d_{i,j} = d_{j,i}$
  • 4) Triangle inequality $d_{i,j} ≤ d_{ik} + d_{jk}$

if $4_{th}$ condition is respected then we have a distance

Similarity measures¶

  • Euclidean $\rightarrow$ boss of straight line
  • City Block, Manhattan $\rightarrow$ boss of the street
  • Chebyshev $\rightarrow$ boss of trading stocks
  • Cosine $\rightarrow$ rulez nlp
  • Mahalanobis $\rightarrow$ when euclidean fails to give real distance between observation :/
  • Jaccard $\rightarrow$ bff of cosine (dw about duplication)

Unsupervised : Reduce Dimensionality¶

the curse of dimensionality

what?

  • projects the original high-dimensional input data to a low-dimensional space

why?

  • identify patterns and solve large-scale computationally expensive problems

how?

  • filtering out the not-so-relevant features and keeping as much of the interesting ones as possible

yes but how

  • linear & nonlinear

Linear Projection¶

  • linearly projecting data from a high-dimensioanl space to a low-dimensional space

Principal Component Analysis¶

  • identify which features out of the full set of features are most important in explaining the variability among the instances in the data

  • each component is a linear combination of all the variables and is perpendicular to every other component

  • J≤K

  • lose some of the variance by moving to this low-dimensional space

  • perform tasks like clustering more efficiently

  • your data should be numeric and scaled!

PCA¶

  • it calculates the correlation and if this is very high among a subset of the features, PCA will attempt to combine the highly correlated features and represent this data with a smaller number of linearly uncorrelated features
  • the algorithm keeps performing this correlation reduction, finding the directions of maximum variance in the original high dimensional data and projecting them into a smaller dimensional space
  • these newly derived components are known as principal components

In [4]:
from sklearn import decomposition
from sklearn.preprocessing import StandardScaler

X = StandardScaler().fit_transform(iris[['sepal length','sepal width','petal length','petal width']].values)
y = iris.target.values

pca = decomposition.PCA()
principalcomponents = pca.fit_transform(X)

df_2 = pd.DataFrame(principalcomponents)

principalcomponents_df = pd.concat([df_2,iris],axis=1).rename(columns = {0:'PC1',1:'PC2',2:'PC3',3:'PC4'})

Sparse PCA¶

  • a version of PCA that retains some degree of sparsity controlled by a hyperparameter called $\alpha$
  • the algorithm searches for linear combinations in just some of the input variables, reducing the original feature space to some degree but not as compactly as normal PCA
In [7]:
#https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.decomposition.SparsePCA.html
from sklearn.decomposition import SparsePCA
sparsePCA = decomposition.SparsePCA(alpha=0.0001)

principalcomponents = sparsePCA.fit_transform(X)

df_2 = pd.DataFrame(principalcomponents)

principalcomponents_df = pd.concat([df_2,iris],axis=1).rename(columns = {0:'PC1',1:'PC2',2:'PC3',3:'PC4'})

Kernel PCA¶

  • runs a similarity function (kernel method) over pairs of original data points in order to perform nonlinear dimensionality reduction (dark side of PCA)
  • maps the implicit feature space where the majority of data points lie and creates this implicit feature space in a much smaller number of dimensions than the dimensions in the original feature set
  • effective when the original feature set is not linearly separable
In [9]:
#https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.decomposition.KernelPCA.html
from sklearn.decomposition import KernelPCA

kernelPCA = KernelPCA (kernel='rbf', n_components=2) #radial basis function kernel

principalcomponents = kernelPCA.fit_transform(X)

df_2 = pd.DataFrame(principalcomponents)

principalcomponents_df = pd.concat([df_2,iris],axis=1).rename(columns = {0:'PC1',1:'PC2'})
principalcomponents_df.head(5)

Random Projection¶

  • Johnson–Lindenstrauss lemma, projecting points from a high dimensional space (very huge!) to a space of much lower dimensions
  • scale of distances between the points is preserved
  • robust to outliers

Gaussian Random Projection¶

  • standard version of Random Projection
  • parameter eps to set since it controls the quality of the embedding where smaller values generate a higher number of dimensions
In [11]:
#https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.random_projection.GaussianRandomProjection.html
from sklearn.random_projection import GaussianRandomProjection

GRP = GaussianRandomProjection(n_components=2, eps = 0.5)

vectors_ = GRP.fit_transform(X)

df_2 = pd.DataFrame(vectors_)

vectors_df = pd.concat([df_2,iris],axis=1).rename(columns = {0:'Vector 1',1:'Vector 2'})
vectors_df.head(5)

Sparse Random Projection¶

  • sparse version of Random Projection
  • it retains some degree of sparsity in the transformed feature set and is generally much more efficient, transforming the original data into the reduced space much faster than normal Gaussian random projection

Manifold Learning¶

  • can be thought of as an attempt to generalize linear frameworks like PCA to be sensitive to non-linear structure in data
  • manifold are smooth, curved surfaces within the multidimensional space

ISOMAP¶

  • it learns the intrinsic geometry of the original data based on where each point lies relative to its neighbors on a manifold

In [15]:
#https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.manifold.Isomap.html
from sklearn.manifold import Isomap

isomap = Isomap(n_neighbors = 2)

vectors_ = isomap.fit_transform(X)

df_2 = pd.DataFrame(vectors_)

vectors_df = pd.concat([df_2,iris],axis=1).rename(columns = {0:'Vector 1',1:'Vector 2'})

Locally Linear Embedding¶

  • this method preserves distances within local neighborhoods as it projects the data from the original feature space to a reduced space

  • LLE discovers the nonlinear structure in the original high-dimensional data by segmenting the data into smaller components and modeling each component as a linear embedding

In [17]:
#https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.manifold.LocallyLinearEmbedding.html
from sklearn.manifold import LocallyLinearEmbedding

lle = LocallyLinearEmbedding(n_components = 2, n_neighbors=5, method='modified')

vectors_ = lle.fit_transform(X)

df_2 = pd.DataFrame(vectors_)

vectors_df = pd.concat([df_2,iris],axis=1).rename(columns = {0:'Vector 1',1:'Vector 2'})
vectors_df.head(5)

t-Distributed Stocastic Neighbor Embedding¶

  • embeds high-dimensional data into a space of just two or three dimensions

  • similar instances are modeled closer together and dissimilar instances are modeled further away

  • t-SNE has a nonconvex cost function, which means that different initializations of the algorithm will generate different results $\rightarrow\$ no stable solution

  • in real-world applications of t-SNE, it is best to use another dimensionality reduction technique (such as PCA) to reduce the number of dimensions before applying t-SNE. In this way we reduce the noise in the features that are fed into t-SNE and speed up the computation of the algorithm

In [19]:
from sklearn.manifold import TSNE
#https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.manifold.TSNE.html

tSNE = TSNE()

vectors_ = tSNE.fit_transform(X)

df_2 = pd.DataFrame(vectors_)

Other Type of Reduction¶

Dictionary Learning¶

  • learns the sparse representation of the original data.
  • the matrix (known as the dictionary) is mostly populated by zeros with only a few nonzero weights
  • the vectors in the dictionary are known as atoms
  • identify the most salient representative elements of the original feature space and these are the ones that have the most nonzero weights
In [22]:
from sklearn.decomposition import DictionaryLearning
#https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.decomposition.DictionaryLearning.html

dictionarylearning = DictionaryLearning(n_components = 2)

vectors_ = dictionarylearning.fit_transform(X)

df_2 = pd.DataFrame(vectors_)

vectors_df = pd.concat([df_2,iris],axis=1).rename(columns = {0:'Vector 1',1:'Vector 2'})
vectors_df.head(5)

Indipendent Component Analysis¶

  • is commonly used in signal processing tasks (for example, to identify the individual voices in an audio clip of a busy coffeehouse)
  • the blended signals are separate into their individual components and after the separation is complete, any original characteristic is reconstructed by adding some combination of the individual components that are generated

In [24]:
from sklearn.decomposition import FastICA
#https://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/generated/sklearn.decomposition.FastICA.html

fastICA = FastICA(n_components=2, algorithm = 'parallel')

vectors_ = fastICA.fit_transform(X)

df_2 = pd.DataFrame(vectors_)

vectors_df = pd.concat([df_2,iris],axis=1).rename(columns = {0:'Vector 1',1:'Vector 2'})
